The defendant Elijah Ali Cannedy was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property <=$2500 - Party to a Crime [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).
  • Entry into/onto Bldg/Constuct.Site/Room [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.15(1).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Defendant Elijah Ali Cannedy in court with attorney Scott Paley Phillips Law Offices.  Michael Jerome Lonski appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, Defense and Defendant.  

AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Corrections,  consecutive to any other sentence.  Court STAYED sentence and placed the defendant on PROBATION for a period of 2 YEARS with the following conditions:
-Restitution in the amount of $545 joint and several with any and all other co-actors that have been convicted, to Marvin J. and Emily R.  Restitution to be paid before any court costs, surcharges and assessments
-Court costs and victim/witness surcharges are to be collected during term of probation; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment
-No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
-No association with drug users, drug dealers and drug houses  or otherwise engage in drug dealing
-Cooperate with agent
-Obtain/maintain employment unless in school.  If in school full-time, defendant to have a part-time job; if defendant is in school part-time, defendant to have a full-time job 
-Obtain high school diploma,  GED or HSED
-Successfully complete a Cognitive Thinking Behavioral Modification Program
-Mental health assessment and any recommended treatment to include any counseling, therapy and taking any prescribed medications
-No contact with Marvin J. and Emily R. 
-AODA assessment and any recommended treatment
-Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzers
-No alcohol or controlled substances
-Court allows for expungement if defendant successfully completes all condition of probation.

AS TO COUNT 2:
The Court sentenced defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Corrections,  consecutive to any other.  Court STAYED sentence and placed the defendant on PROBATION for a period of 2 YEARS with the following conditions:
-Court costs and victim/witness surcharges are to be collected during term of probation; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment
-No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
-No association with drug users, drug dealers and drug houses  or otherwise engage in drug dealing
-Cooperate with agent
-Obtain/maintain employment unless in school.  If in school full-time, defendant to have a part-time job; if defendant is in school part-time, defendant to have a full-time job 
-Obtain high school diploma,  GED or HSED
-Successfully complete a Cognitive Thinking Behavioral Modification Program
-Mental health assessment and any recommended treatment to include any counseling, therapy and taking any prescribed medications
-No contact with Marvin J. and Emily R. 
-AODA assessment and any recommended treatment
-Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzers
-No alcohol or controlled substances
-Court allows for expungement if defendant successfully completes all condition of probation.

AS TO COUNT 3:
Court ordered defendant serve 90 DAYS in the House of Corrections, consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 6 days time served, with Huber release privileges for school, verifiable work, day reporting center, medical care treatment.  No electronic monitoring.  Good time credit allowed.  Defendant to start serving his sentencing on August 3, 2015 at 6:00 p.m.
